page.title: 02LANDSCAPE
page.content: The relief of the area is generally low-lying with the majority of it about 4-5 metres above sea level. The main low lying areas are either side of the River Ouse which flows from south to north through the middle of the area. There are two areas of higher ground, one to the east which rises to 20 metres above sea level and one to the east which reaches 11 metres above sea level. The shape of the ground on the higher areas is very gently undulating with no steep slopes, contour lines are few and far between and in fact the only one is the 15 metre line found in the eastern half of the area. The remainder of the area has no contour lines on it at all.
